column8: The character WYNN was originally a Runic letter in the common Germanic runic alphabet, ᚹ (16B9), called wynn in the Anglo-Saxon Rune poem. It was borrowed into the Latin alphabet in England to denote /w/ and is usually rendered with ‹w› in simplified transcriptions.

column5: LATIN SMALL LETTER VEND
LATIN CAPITAL LETTER VEND
column8:
distinguish it from ‹y›. It was used to denote /v/ and is always rendered with ‹v› in simplified transcriptions. Since it was borrowed from Old English, it is
usually referred to as an Insular character, although it ultimately derives from the Runic alphabet. However, at the time of borrowing in the 11th century,
the runic character ᚹ (16B9) had been replaced by ᚢ (16A2) in the younger futhark.

FULL STOP
column8: The full stop is often used as a mark of abbreviation, typically in suspended (truncated) words. If an encoder wants to make a distinction between the full stop as a punctuation mark and as an abbreviation mark, we recommend that the same character, 002E FULL STOP, should be used in both cases, but that the abbreviation mark is specified by markup, e.g. by the <am> element in the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) P5 Guidelines.

column5: SEMICOLON
column8: In Medieval script, a sign looking like the semicolon was commonly used as an abbreviation for ‘eð’ or ‘ed’, cf. LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SEMICOLON at F1AC on p. 136 below. If an encoder wants to use 003B SEMICOLON for the abbreviation sign, we recommend that this usage should be specified by markup, e.g. by the <am> element in the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) P5 Guidelines.

column5: AMPERSAND
column8: In Medieval primary sources, the ampersand was used as an abbreviation for the conjunction ‘and’ (Latin ‘et’, Medieval Nordic ‘ok’, etc.), in which case it can be specified by markup, e.g. by the <am> element in the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) P5 Guidelines.

column5: LATIN SMALL LETTER SHARP S
column8: In Medieval sources, the “sharp s” can also be used as an abbreviation character, in which case it may be specified by markup, e.g. by the <am> element.

column5: GREEK CAPITAL LETTER THETA
GREEK SMALL LETTER THETA
column8: The theta characters are sometimes used as an abbreviation sign for obiit ‘he/she died’, but we recommend using the alternative obiit pair of characters below. See also the introduction in Ernst W.E. Hübner, Exempla Scripturae Epigraphicae Latinae, Berlin: Reimer 1885 (rpt. Berlin: de Gruyter, 1979), in which he states that the theta should be kept apart from the obiit sign (barred ‘o’).

column5: LATIN SMALL LETTER O WITH LONG STROKE OVERLAY
LATIN CAPITAL LETTER O WITH LONG STROKE OVERLAY
column8: As pointed out above, the character 03B8 GREEK SMALL LETTER THETA in Greek and Coptic is sometimes used for rendering this abbreviation, but we recommend having a separate obiit character.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SMALL ET
column8: The Unicode descriptive name for this character is TIRONIAN SIGN ET. It was frequently used in Medieval sources, and is still used in Modern Irish.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SMALL ET WITH STROKE
LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN CAPITAL ET
LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN CAPITAL ET WITH STROKE
MODIFIER LETTER APOSTROPHE
column8: The ordinary apostrophe, 0027 APOSTROPHE, has been listed in section 5 below. We recommend that the character 02BC should be used to encode ab­breviations, and that 0027 should be used in all other contexts.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN ESSE
column8: The Unicode descriptive name for this character is ALMOST EQUAL TO.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN EST
column8: The Unicode descriptive name for this character is HOMOTHETIC.

column5: LATIN SMALL LETTER CON
LATIN CAPITAL LETTER CON
column8: Another form of the ‘con’ abbreviation character looks like a reversed ‘C’. This character, which also was used as a Roman numeral and as a Claudian letter, antisigma, has been listed under the character ‘C’ above.

column5: LATIN SMALL LETTER REVERSED C WITH DOT
LATIN CAPITAL LETTER REVERSED C WITH DOT
LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SPACING BASE-LINE US
column8: This character is positioned on the base line, but not with full height.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SPACING BASE-LINE CAPITAL US
column8: This character is positioned on the base line and has capital form (full height).

column5: MODIFIER LETTER US
column8: This character is positioned above the base line, the top aligning with the top of ascenders.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN AUTEM
LATIN SMALL LETTER RUM ROTUNDA
LATIN CAPITAL LETTER RUM ROTUNDA

LATIN CAPITAL LETTER IS
LATIN SMALL LETTER UM
column8: This character can also be used for the ‘soldi’ sign (see p. 159 below)

column5: LATIN SMALL LETTER ET
LATIN CAPITAL LETTER ET
column8: The two characters above are used as suspension marks in a number of contexts, e.g. for ‘et’ in ‘videlicet’, for ‘us’ in ‘quibus’, ‘omnibus’, for ‘ue’ in ‘ne­que’, ‘cumque’, for ‘m’ in ‘nam’, ‘omnem’, for ‘est‘ in ‘prodest’, ‘interest’, etc. In the paleographical literature, it is usually described as “a sign looking like the number 3”. It is difficult to find a wholly suitable name; the name proposed here takes the abbreviation of ‘et’ in ‘videlicet’ to be prototypical.

column5: LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SEMICOLON
column8: The character 003B SEMICOLON can be used for the frequent abbreviation sign of similar shape. However, some encoders might want to have a separate character, in which case we recommend using F1AC LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN SEMICOLON. Neither character should be unified with F1EA PUNCTUS VERSUS, which is a punctuation mark (see p. 147 below).

column5: RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER F
column8: Runes are alphabetical signs in their own right, but in Medieval Nordic manuscripts written in the Latin alphabet they function as abbreviation characters, e.g. the ‘f’ rune, meaning ‘fé’ (cattle and/or goods). The Unicode descriptive name for this character is RUNIC LETTER FEHU FEOH FE F, but here a simpler name has been given, RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER F.

column5: RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER M
column8: In Medieval Nordic manuscripts written in the Latin alphabet, the ‘m’ rune serves as an abbreviation for ‘maðr’ (man). The Unicode descriptive name for this character is RUNIC LETTER LONG-BRANCH-MADR M, but here a simpler name has been given, RUNIC MEDIEVAL LETTER M.

column5: L B BAR SYMBOL
column8: Used as an abbreviation for the weight unity ‘pound’. For variants, see section 7 Symbols below.

column5: REVERSE SOLIDUS
LEFT UPPER SLANTED STROKE
column8:
The Unicode descriptive name is LEFT RAISED OMISSION BRACKET, but the more general LEFT UPPER SLANTED STROKE has been chosen here. In
Medieval Nordic editing, it is typically used to indicate the beginning of text added above the line.

column5: RIGHT UPPER SLANTED STROKE
column8:
The Unicode descriptive name is RIGHT RAISED OMISSION BRACKET, but the more general RIGHT UPPER SLANTED STROKE has been chosen here. In
Medieval Nordic editing, it is typically used to indicate the end of text added above the line.

column5: RIGHT LOWER SLANTED STROKE
column8: The Unicode descriptive name is LEFT LOW PARAPHRASE BRACKET, but the more general name RIGHT LOWER SLANTED STROKE has been chosen here. In Medieval Nordic editing, it is typically used to indicate the end of text added in the margin and is for this reason called ‘RIGHT’ (by analogy with e.g. 0029 RIGHT PARENTHESIS).

column5: LEFT LOWER SLANTED STROKE
column8: The Unicode descriptive name is RIGHT LOW PARAPHRASE BRACKET, but the more general name LEFT LOWER SLANTED STROKE has been chosen here. In Medieval Nordic editing, it is typically used to indicate the beginning of text added in the margin and is for this reason called ‘LEFT’ (by analogy with e.g. 0028 LEFT PARENTHESIS).

column8: As the name HYPHEN-MINUS indicates, this character is ambiguous. For an unambiguous hyphen character, see 2010 HYPHEN in General Punctuation immediately below, and for an unambiguous minus character, see 2212 MINUS in Mathematical Operators (p. 160).

column5: HYPHEN
column8: This is an unambiguous hyphen character.

In such cases, we recommend that the character 02BC LATIN ABBREVIATION SIGN APOSTROPHE in section 4 above should be used.

column5: RIGHT-POINTING DOUBLE ANGLE QUOTATION MARK
RIGHT ANGLE BRACKET
column8:
The Unicode descriptive name is MATHEMATICAL RIGHT ANGLE BRACKET, but the word ‘MATHEMATICAL’ has been left out here. This bracket is typically
used to indicate the end of an editorial addition (supplied text).

column5: DISTINCTIO
column8: Described by the grammarian Donatus, who distinguishes between three positions of the dot: on the baseline (to be unified with 002E FULL STOP), middle height (to be unified with 00B7 MIDDLE DOT) and the high dot, shown here. See also Isidore of Sevilla, Etymologiae I 20. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 13, says that the distinctio was used to indicate “a final pause, after a periodus, or where the sententia is completed”.

column5: COMMA POSITURA
column8: The positura is similar to COMMA 002C, but should be kept apart from this punctuation mark due to a different and more specialised usage. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 306.

column5: HIGH COMMA POSITURA (SIMPLEX DUCTUS)
column8: Similar form as the positura, but positioned above the ‘x’ height. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 307.

column5: PUNCTUS VERSUS
column8: Similar in shape to the semicolon (003B), but should be kept apart from this mark. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301, 306.

column5: PUNCTUS WITH COMMA POSITURA
column8: Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 306.

column5: COLON WITH MIDDLE COMMA POSITURA
column8: Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 306.

column5: TWO DOTS OVER COMMA POSITURA
column8: Attested in Old Icelandic, e.g. in Holm perg 15 B 4to (see Hreinn Benediktsson, Early Icelandic Script, Reykjavík 1965, pl. 8:14) and in GKS 2365 4to (Codex Regius of the Eddic poems).

column5: THREE DOTS WITH COMMA POSITURA
column8: This punctuation mark looks like an upwards-poiting triangle of dots with a comma between (and below) the two lower dots. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 307. See also 2234 above in Mathematical Operators.

column5: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS
column8: This form of the punctus elevatus is typically found in English manuscripts and is sometimes seen as the default form. Sometimes called ‘tick and point’, e.g. by N.R. Ker, English Manuscripts in the Century after the Norman Conquest, Oxford, 1960, p. 46.

column5: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS DIAGONAL STROKE
column8: Variant form of the punctus elevatus.

column5: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS WITH HIGH BACK
column8: Variant form of the punctus elevatus found in manuscripts in the Low countries, eastern France and the Rhineland.

column5: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS WITH ONSET
column8: Variant form of the punctus elevatus found in manuscripts from southern Germany.

column5: PUNCTUS FLEXUS
column8:
Looks like the digit 7 with a dot below, sometimes referred to as ‘seven and point’ (e.g. by N.R. Ker, English Manuscripts in the Century after the Norman
Conquest, Oxford, 1960, p. 47). Also called PUNCTUS CIRCUMFLEXUS. Used to mark sentence-medial pauses, especially in liturgical texts where the pitch
of the voice drops. Cf. also Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301, 306. Note that the shape in Parkes’ book looks more like an
open ‘a’ than ‘7’, but this is basically a question of variance.

column5: PUNCTUS EXCLAMATIVUS
column8: Early form with two dots below each other and a diagonal stroke on top of them. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 301.

column5: PUNCTUS INTERROGATIVUS
PUNCTUS INTERROGATIVUS HORIZONTAL TILDE
column8: This is a variant of the question mark where the swash (tilde) is horizontal. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 301.

column5: PUNCTUS INTERROGATIVUS LEMNISKATE FORM
column8: Attested in Old Icelandic, but very marginal. For examples, see Holm perg 15 B 4to (cf. Hreinn Benediktsson, Early Icelandic Script, Reykjavík 1965, pl. 8:13 and 8:19).

column5: REVERSED QUESTION MARK
column8: Looks like a horizontally flipped (i.e. reversed) modern question mark, called PUNCTUS PERCONTATIVUS. Used in late texts to mark the end of a question that does not require an answer (i.e. a rhetorical question), as opposed to the PUNCTUS INTERROGATIVUS.

column5: WAVY LINE
column8: Frequently used in English manuscripts in the 12th century in the form of a wavy line or sometimes a straight line. Placed slightly above the base line.

column5: MEDIEVAL COMMA
column8: Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 301. According to Parkes, this mark “appears most frequently in the work of fourteenth-century Italian scribes” (p. 303).

column5: PARAGRAPHUS
column8: Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 12, 43, 305.

column5: SIGNE DE RENVOI
column8: Looks like two dots over a single dot. Used to connect a marginal note to a place in the text. Looks similar to TWO DOTS OVER ONE DOT PUNCTUATION below, but has a different usage and the dots are more widely spaced.

column5: TWO DOTS OVER ONE DOT PUNCTUATION
column8: Similar to 2235 BECAUSE in Mathematical Operators, but should be recognised as a separate punctuation character and given its own code point.

column5: ONE DOT OVER TWO DOTS PUNCTUATION
column8: Similar to 2234 THEREFORE in Mathematical Operators, but should be recognised as a separate punctuation character and given its own code point.

column5: FOUR DOTS PUNCTUATION
column8: Similar to 2237 PROPORTION in Mathematical Operators, but should be recognised as a separate punctuation character and given its own code point.

column5: FIVE DOT MARK
VIRGULA SUSPENSIVA
column8: Looks like a solidus with a dot in the middle. Used to mark a very brief pause or hesitation in the text. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 307.

column5: SHORT VIRGULA
column8: Looks like a virgule, but confined within the ‘x’ height (like a half-height slash), e.g. ‘x  x’. Attested in late paper manuscripts of Medieval Nordic verse and not to be unified with the ordinary comma.

column5: DIPLE WITH DOT
column8: The Unicode name for this character is GREATER-THAN WITH DOT, but it can also be used as a punctuation mark and is therefore given another name here, DIPLE WITH DOT. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 303.

In SGML/XML encoded documents, the ampersand is the opening character of an entity name, as exemplified throughout this recommendation. To avoid
confusion, the ampersand as such can be encoded with the entity ‘&’. In Medieval primary sources, the ampersand was used as an abbreviation for
the conjunction ‘and’ (Latin ‘et’, Medieval Nordic ‘ok’, etc.), in which case it can be specified by markup, e.g. by the <am> element in the Text Encoding
Initiative (TEI) P5 Guidelines.

column9: This sign is commonly used in editions to indicate illegible characters. It has the same shape as the digit ‘0’, but is only of ‘x’ height: ‘x  x’.

MULTIPLICATION SIGN
column8: The Unicode character 00D7 MULTIPLICATION SIGN can also be used as an encoding for METRICAL ANCEPS. We recommend retaining the entity name ‘×’ also in this context.

column5: FIGURE DASH
column8: The Unicode character 2012 FIGURE DASH can also be used as an encoding for METRICAL LONGUM. We recommend retaining the entity name ‘&numdash;’ also in this context.

METRICAL SYMBOL ANCEPS
column8:
As stated above, this character can be encoded with 00D7 MULTIPLICATION SIGN and the entity name ‘×’ (p. 164 above). We recommend that this
code point should be used hereafter. However, for those who would like to continue using the complete set of metrical symbols in the Private Use Area, we
recommend that the character F70A should be given the entity name ‘&metranc;’ and the descriptive name METRICAL SYMBOL ANCEPS.

point should be used hereafter. However, for those who would like to continue using the complete set of metrical symbols in the Private Use Area, we recommend

METRICAL SYMBOL BREVE ABOVE LONGUM (SHORT OR LONG SYLLABLE)
column9: In v. 4.1 of the Unicode Standard, this character was assigned to code point 23D3 in Miscellaneous Technical (see p. 164 above). We recommend that this code point should be used hereafter. However, for those who would like to continue using the complete set of metrical symbols in the Private Use Area, we recommend that the character F702 should be given the entity name ‘&metrmacrbreve;’ and the descriptive name METRICAL SYMBOL BREVE ABOVE LONGUM (SHORT OR LONG SYLLABLE).

METRICAL SYMBOL RESOLVED LIFT
column8: In v. 4.1 of the Unicode Standard, the character METRICAL SYMBOL RESOLVED LIFT was assigned to code point 23D4 in Miscellaneous Technical and given the descriptive name METRICAL LONG OVER TWO SHORTS (see p. 164 above). We recommend that this code point should be used hereafter. Howe­ver, for those who would like to continue using the complete set of metrical symbols in the Private Use Area, we recommend that the character F72E should be given the entity name ‘&metrdblbrevemacr;’ and the descriptive name METRICAL SYMBOL LONGUM ABOVE BREVE (SHORT OR LONG SYLLABLE).

METRICAL SYMBOL PAUSE
column8:
As stated above, this character can be encoded with 2227 LOGICAL AND and the entity name ‘&logand;’ (p. 155). We recommend that this code point
should be used hereafter. However, for those who would like to continue using the complete set of metrical symbols in the Private Use Area, we recommend
that the character F714 should be given the entity name ‘&metrpause;’ and the descriptive name METRICAL SYMBOL PAUSE.
